I have an Angular landing page with dark background hero headers (h1, h2). 
I want a lightweight hover distortion effect — no WebGL, no SVG filters, 
no GSAP. Pure CSS + minimal vanilla TypeScript only.

The effect should feel organic and slightly glitchy — NOT a simple scale/color 
transition. Think: text that feels unstable when you touch it.

---

### The effect: CSS clip-path slice distortion

On hover, split the heading into 3 visual slices that each shift 
independently on different axes, giving a "broken signal" / holographic 
fragmentation feel. This is done entirely with CSS pseudo-elements and 
custom properties — zero JS except for the mousemove offset.

---

### 1. HTML structure

Wrap each header in a span with data attribute for the text:

<h1>
  <span class="glitch-text" data-text="Your Heading Here">
    Your Heading Here
  </span>
</h1>

The data-text value must exactly match the visible text — it's used by 
::before and ::after to clone the text for layer stacking.

---

### 2. SCSS — complete implementation

.glitch-text {
  position: relative;
  display: inline-block;
  color: #ffffff;
  cursor: default;

  /* Base text — always clean */

  &::before,
  &::after {
    content: attr(data-text);
    position: absolute;
    top: 0;
    left: 0;
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    opacity: 0;
    transition: opacity 0.1s;
  }

  /* Slice 1 — shifts right, clips top third, cyan tint */
  &::before {
    color: #00ffff;
    clip-path: polygon(0 0, 100% 0, 100% 33%, 0 33%);
    transform: translateX(0px);
  }

  /* Slice 2 — shifts left, clips bottom third, red tint */  
  &::after {
    color: #ff003c;
    clip-path: polygon(0 66%, 100% 66%, 100% 100%, 0 100%);
    transform: translateX(0px);
  }

  &:hover::before,
  &:hover::after {
    opacity: 1;
  }

  /* On hover, CSS custom properties drive the shift amounts */
  &:hover::before {
    transform: translateX(var(--shift-x, 4px));
    animation: glitch-slice-top 0.3s steps(1) forwards;
  }

  &:hover::after {
    transform: translateX(calc(var(--shift-x, -4px) * -1));
    animation: glitch-slice-bottom 0.3s steps(1) forwards;
  }
}

/* Keyframe — snaps between 3-4 offset positions, not smooth — 
   this is intentional, smooth = cheap, stepped = premium glitch */
@keyframes glitch-slice-top {
  0%   { transform: translateX(3px);  clip-path: polygon(0 0, 100% 0, 100% 33%, 0 33%); }
  25%  { transform: translateX(-2px); clip-path: polygon(0 5%, 100% 5%, 100% 38%, 0 38%); }
  50%  { transform: translateX(5px);  clip-path: polygon(0 0, 100% 0, 100% 28%, 0 28%); }
  75%  { transform: translateX(-3px); clip-path: polygon(0 2%, 100% 2%, 100% 35%, 0 35%); }
  100% { transform: translateX(4px);  clip-path: polygon(0 0, 100% 0, 100% 33%, 0 33%); }
}

@keyframes glitch-slice-bottom {
  0%   { transform: translateX(-3px); clip-path: polygon(0 66%, 100% 66%, 100% 100%, 0 100%); }
  25%  { transform: translateX(4px);  clip-path: polygon(0 62%, 100% 62%, 100% 95%, 0 95%); }
  50%  { transform: translateX(-5px); clip-path: polygon(0 68%, 100% 68%, 100% 100%, 0 100%); }
  75%  { transform: translateX(2px);  clip-path: polygon(0 64%, 100% 64%, 100% 98%, 0 98%); }
  100% { transform: translateX(-4px); clip-path: polygon(0 66%, 100% 66%, 100% 100%, 0 100%); }
}

